The paper introduces a cognitive model for constructing human-like questions, which involves treating questions as formal programs that output an answer when executed on the state of the world. This approach falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), natural language processing (cs.CL), and machine learning (cs.LG). The evaluation of the model involves modeling the types of questions generated by humans in a game, which could also fall under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper discusses the importance of question complexity and informativeness, which could relate to the sub-category of software engineering (cs.SD).
